const e="stellar-recipe-app",t={title:"Stellar — AI Recipe App",subtitle:"AI-powered mobile app that turns whatever's in your fridge into a recipe",company:"Side Project",year:"2024",duration:"Solo project",role:"Sole Designer",team_size:"1",cover_color:"#111111",tags:["Mobile Design","AI","UX Research","Side Project"]},s=[{id:"overview",label:"Overview",type:"hero",data:{headline:"An AI that earns trust slowly, in a world where the first session is the only one that matters.",body:"Stellar is a solo design sprint exploring what it actually takes to make AI-powered recipe generation feel trustworthy — not just technically correct. Research kept returning to the same contradiction: users wanted the AI to decide for them, but any sign of arbitrariness collapsed trust in the whole system. The design challenge wasn't building an AI that generated good recipes. It was building one that felt considered on day one — before it had any behavioral data to work with.",image:null,stats:[{label:"Year",value:"2024"},{label:"My Role",value:"Sole Designer"},{label:"Team",value:"Solo"},{label:"Type",value:"Side Project"}]}},{id:"problem",label:"The Problem",type:"statement",creative_direction:{tone:"reframe",notes:"Blur-in for the problem headline — it's a revelation. The real problem wasn't what you expected."},motion_spec:{enter:"blur_in",duration:.9,easing:"fast_out"},data:{eyebrow:"The Problem",headline:"People don't have a recipe problem. They have a decision problem.",body:`There are more recipes online than anyone could cook in a lifetime. The problem isn't access — it's the daily 6pm question of 'what do I actually make tonight?' with a half-empty fridge, 30 minutes, and decision fatigue from the rest of the day.

Existing apps made it worse. More filters, more browsing, more scrolling. The opportunity wasn't to add more recipes — it was to take the decision off the user entirely.`}},{id:"research",label:"Research",type:"text_media",creative_direction:{tone:"evidence",notes:"Slides from left — text leads, data follows. Research section should feel like evidence arriving."},motion_spec:{enter:"slide_left",duration:.75,stagger:.1,easing:"fast_out",y_enter:32},data:{layout:"text_left",eyebrow:"User Research",headline:"Investigating habits, frustrations, and attitudes toward AI in the kitchen.",body:"20+ users surveyed, 6 interviewed in depth. Methods: quantitative online survey, empathy mapping, Jobs to Be Done framework. The goal wasn't to validate assumptions — it was to find where cooking actually breaks down for real people.",image:!0,image_hint:"Empathy map or affinity board from interview synthesis — clusters around 'decision fatigue', 'fridge contents', 'trust in AI suggestions'"}},{id:"research-stats",type:"stat_grid",creative_direction:{tone:"evidence",notes:"Numbers do the talking here — drop them in cleanly after the research narrative. Fast stagger, feels like data arriving."},motion_spec:{enter:"fade_up",duration:.6,stagger:.1,easing:"fast_out"},data:{eyebrow:"What the numbers said",stats:[{value:"70%",label:"wanted recipes based on what's already in their fridge",context:"Primary survey, n=20+"},{value:"85%",label:"found AI diet-tailored suggestions very helpful",context:"Primary survey, n=20+"},{value:"65%",label:"said visual appeal directly drove their decision to try a dish",context:"Primary survey, n=20+"},{value:"~60%",label:"expected to use an AI recipe app at least weekly",context:"Stated intent (not behaviour)"}],note:"All figures from primary quantitative survey (20+ respondents) and 6 in-depth interviews conducted during the research sprint. These are self-reported preferences, not observed behaviour — stated intent figures should be treated as directional, not predictive."}},{id:"user-needs",label:"User Needs",type:"affinity_map",data:{title:"Three things users couldn't stop talking about.",clusters:[{category:"Meal Planning Challenges",items:["Tired of cooking the same recipes every week","No time to plan — meal planning feels like another task","Overwhelmed in the kitchen, need something that simplifies","Picky eater with specific taste preferences","Busy traveler who wants to keep up with new cuisines"]},{category:"Food Waste Concerns",items:["Hate throwing away ingredients before using them","Wasting money on groceries that expire unused","Environmental guilt around food waste","No system for tracking what's in the fridge"]},{category:"Recipe Organization",items:["No system to organize saved recipes","Recipes scattered across apps, screenshots, bookmarks","Too much time searching online for something already seen","Wish for a personalized, searchable recipe book"]}]}},{id:"trust-tensions",label:"The Core Tension",type:"insight_cards",creative_direction:{tone:"reframe",notes:"This is the pivot — the case study spine. Each card is a contradiction that shaped every design decision."},motion_spec:{enter:"fade_up",duration:.7,stagger:.12,easing:"fast_out"},data:{eyebrow:"What the research kept returning to",items:[{icon:"🤖",headline:"Users wanted AI to decide — but not feel like it was guessing",body:"Every interview surfaced the same paradox: people wanted AI to take the decision off their plate, but any hint of arbitrariness collapsed trust instantly. One confusing suggestion — a recipe with an ingredient they'd never heard of — was enough to make the whole system feel unreliable. The design challenge wasn't accuracy. It was legibility: making the AI's reasoning feel considered, not random."},{icon:"🥄",headline:"The real entry point is the fridge, not the search bar",body:"The existing mental model for recipe apps is browse → save → cook. But the actual 6pm problem is: 'I have these 7 things. What can I make right now?' That's not a search query — it's a constraint. Reframing the entry point from recipe-search to ingredient-input changed what the entire product was trying to solve, and immediately separated Stellar from every existing competitor."},{icon:"📉",headline:"First-session trust was the entire product problem",body:"Users who received one confusing suggestion in their first session assumed the whole system was unreliable. There was no recovery path — no explanation of why the AI suggested what it did, no way to correct it, no signal that the next result would be better. The first session wasn't just important for retention. It was the only session that mattered for trust."}]}},{id:"hmw",type:"quote",data:{text:"How might we develop a recipe generator that creates new recipes based on users' favorite ingredients?"}},{id:"persona",label:"Who We Designed For",type:"personas",data:{title:"The person the design had to earn.",items:[{name:"Maya",type:"Product Designer · 29 · Decision-fatigued after work",biography:"Spends her day making decisions — design, product, people. By 6:40pm she has nothing left for 'what should I cook?' She has a rough sense of what's in her fridge and a 30-minute window before she orders delivery.",goal:"Know what she can cook from what's already in her kitchen in under two minutes — no browsing, no planning, no extra trip to the store.",needs:"Ingredient-first entry so she starts with what she has, not what she's searching for. Ingredient match score on result cards so she can see 'you have 8/9 ingredients' before tapping in [ingredient match score]. AI reasoning visible on the suggested recipe — not just the name, but why it fits her history ('Mediterranean, 25 min or less, uses fridge staples') so it doesn't feel arbitrary [AI reasoning display].",frustrations:"Opens a recipe app, searches 'chicken', gets 847 results. Filters by dietary preference, still 200 results. Spends 8 minutes browsing. Orders delivery. Tomorrow she tries again.",why_use:"Maya selects 6 ingredients from her counter. The top result shows '7/9 ingredients matched' — she checks which 2 she's missing and decides to substitute. She taps the card, sees the reasoning ('matches your cooking history: Mediterranean styles, under 30 minutes'), and trusts it. She didn't browse. She didn't decide. She cooked."}]}},{id:"decisions",label:"Design Decisions",type:"pinned_cards",creative_direction:{tone:"reveal",notes:"Four decisions built around the trust paradox — each one a different angle on the same problem."},motion_spec:{enter:"fade_up",duration:.65,stagger:.12,y_enter:20,easing:"fast_out"},data:{eyebrow:"Design Decisions",headline:"Four bets on how to make AI feel trustworthy, not magical.",items:[{number:"01",title:"Ingredient-first input over recipe-first search",description:`**Problem →** Users who search 'pasta recipe' are competing with Google and AllRecipes — it's a solved problem. The actual 6pm question — 'what can I make from these 6 things?' — isn't a search query. It's a constraint.

**A:** Text search as primary input — familiar, fast for users with a specific dish in mind. **B:** Ingredient selection as the primary entry — the app works from constraint, not intent.

**Chose B** — reframes the app's core value away from recipe competition entirely. **Cost:** Users who arrive wanting to cook a specific dish can't use the primary flow — they need a secondary search path the sprint didn't fully design.`},{number:"02",title:"Ingredient match score on result cards before opening",description:`**Problem →** Users opened a recipe only to find they were missing 4 core ingredients. The qualifying criterion — 'can I actually make this right now?' — arrived after the click, not before it.

**A:** Recipe title and image on card; ingredients revealed inside the detail view. **B:** Ingredient match % on the card surface — 'You have 7/9 ingredients'.

**Chose B** — the match score is the qualifying criterion; it belongs before the tap. **Cost:** The % creates a false hierarchy. A recipe using 4 specialty ingredients you already have might be far better than one scoring 9/12 on generic staples. Users over-relied on the number as a proxy for cooking effort, not quality.`},{number:"03",title:"AI reasoning visible on suggestion cards",description:`**Problem →** Users described AI suggestions as 'random' — not because they were wrong, but because there was no signal explaining the choice. Without a reason, every result felt like a guess.

**A:** Show result only — recipe name, image, time. Clean, no qualification. **B:** Add a reasoning line per card: 'Matches your history: Mediterranean, under 30 min, uses pantry staples.'

**Chose B** — the reasoning line was the highest-trust signal in prototype testing. **Cost:** The reasoning is generated from behavioral history. In session 1, when history is thin, it's generic and unconvincing. The most trust-building feature is weakest exactly when trust matters most.`},{number:"04",title:"Expert escalation as trust fallback, not a bonus feature",description:`**Problem →** Users who didn't trust an AI suggestion had nowhere to go. Accept the result, try to edit it (not a cooking app use case), or leave. There was no trust recovery path.

**A:** Let users modify AI-generated recipes — they become the authority when AI falls short. **B:** Offer escalation to culinary experts who could answer specific questions: 'Can I sub the sumac?'

**Chose B** — expert escalation is a trust recovery mechanism, not a bonus feature. **Cost:** The UX is only as good as the experts behind it. An empty or slow expert pool at a critical moment makes the AI failure worse, not better.`}]}},{id:"demo",label:"Try It",type:"demo",data:{eyebrow:"Interactive Demo",headline:"Pick what's in your fridge.",description:"This is the core of the app. Not a filter. Not a search. Just: what do you have, and what can you make right now?",variant:"recipe_collapse"}},{id:"design",label:"Design",type:"text_media",creative_direction:{tone:"companion",notes:"Slides from right — conversation enters the frame. The chat-first design comes to meet the reader."},motion_spec:{enter:"slide_right",duration:.75,stagger:.1,easing:"fast_out",y_enter:32},data:{layout:"text_right",eyebrow:"Design",headline:"AI as a cooking companion, not just a search engine.",body:"The chat experience lets users ask questions, explore recipes, and get cooking advice in real time. When the AI isn't enough, users can escalate to a pool of culinary experts. Conversations worth sharing can be surfaced to the wider Stellar community — turning individual discovery into collective knowledge.",highlights:["Chat-first interface — ask anything cooking-related, get instant context","Expert escalation — route to real culinary professionals when needed","Community sharing — useful conversations benefit the whole user base"]}},{id:"impact",label:"What I Learned",type:"statement",creative_direction:{tone:"honest",notes:"Simple fade_up, no theatrics — this section is honest, not performative. The learning stands on its own."},motion_spec:{enter:"fade_up",duration:.8,delay:.05,y_enter:28,easing:"symmetric"},data:{eyebrow:"Outcome",headline:"The concept is sound. The hardest problem wasn't solved.",body:`Stellar was a self-initiated design sprint, not a shipped product. The four design decisions above are hypotheses tested in prototype — not production-validated outcomes. In prototype sessions, the ingredient match score and AI reasoning line were the highest-trust signals. Users who saw the reasoning ('matches your cooking history') opened recipes at twice the rate of users who saw the card without it.

What wasn't solved: the cold-start problem. Decision 03 — AI reasoning visible on cards — is weakest exactly when trust matters most: session 1, before behavioral history exists. The feature that most builds trust requires the most data to work. Every AI product I've worked on since has started from this tension: the system is most legible when it knows the user, and most opaque when it needs to earn them.`}},{id:"takeaway",label:"Takeaway",type:"word_reveal",data:{eyebrow:"Takeaway",text:"AI earns trust through explanation, not accuracy. The moment it can't show its work is the moment the user decides it's guessing — and they're usually right.",emojis:["🍳","🥕","✨","🍜","🧅","🌿","🫙"]}}],i={id:e,meta:t,sections:s};export{i as default,e as id,t as meta,s as sections};
